<section class="blk blk--cream2">
  <p class="eyebrow">Money &amp; funding</p>
  <h2 class="sec">Money &amp; funding.</h2>

  <h3>Can I donate right now?</h3>
  <p>Not yet. We&rsquo;re seeking fiscal sponsorship before accepting public donations that would qualify for a tax deduction. You can register an intention to give and we&rsquo;ll email you the moment it opens — no money changes hands today.</p>

  <h3>How will you handle money transparently?</h3>
  {{ gap("faq-q-money-transparency", "the Treasury public financial record with internal receipt/approval trail is design-authored detail; July states only transparent financial records when funding begins — author against the funding model. Once live, spending reports in The Treasury (/treasury)") }}

  <h3>Do donations buy influence or votes?</h3>
  <p>Never. There&rsquo;s no payment to vote and no extra influence for donors — that&rsquo;s a core principle, since the whole movement opposes wealth determining outcomes.</p>
</section>

<section class="blk">
  <p class="eyebrow">The evidence</p>
  <h2 class="sec">The evidence.</h2>

  <h3>How do I know your numbers are real?</h3>
  <p>Every figure carries a source, a date, and a confidence label. Anything hypothetical is marked &ldquo;illustrative only.&rdquo; Corrections are logged publicly — see <a href="/receipts">The Receipts</a>.</p>

  <h3>Won&rsquo;t you just overpromise what AI can do?</h3>
  <p>We use careful, task-specific language and publish uncertainty ranges. Where a model shows automation <em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> beat the status quo once energy, capital, and maintenance are counted, we publish that negative result too.</p>

  <h3>Why fifteen sectors?</h3>
  <p>Because living isn&rsquo;t one bill. We map all fifteen essentials and go deep on three first — Shelter, Food, and Energy — to prove the model before expanding. See <a href="/sectors/">the Sectors</a>.</p>
</section>

<section class="blk blk--cream2">
  <p class="eyebrow">Voice &amp; governance</p>
  <h2 class="sec">Voice &amp; governance.</h2>

  <h3>What is the Assembly, and is my vote binding?</h3>
  <p>The Assembly is how supporters propose, prioritise, and review the work, with transparent records. It is <strong>currently advisory</strong>. As the legal structure matures, votes may carry more weight where the law allows — but decisions with legal, fiduciary, or safeguarding duty always rest with responsible leadership and the fiscal sponsor. The exact binding-versus-advisory wording is being finalised and will be published in the governance policy.</p>

